    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, venturing into the fiery realm beyond the Maillard reaction's sweet spot, are we? As the temperature climbs past the 165 degrees Celsius mark, the culinary landscape shifts dramatically. The Maillard reaction, while still occurring, becomes just one part of a larger, more intense chemical saga.\n\nWhen the heat intensifies, pyrolysis takes the stage. Pyrolysis is the thermal decomposition of organic material at elevated temperatures in an inert atmosphere. In the context of our bread crust, this means that the sugars and proteins begin to break down into smaller molecules, such as carbon dioxide, water, and various volatile compounds. This process contributes to the crust's darker color and more intense flavors, but it also marks the beginning of the end for the Maillard reaction's dominance.\n\nAs the temperature continues to rise, we enter the realm of caramelization, a process distinct from the Maillard reaction. Caramelization involves the thermal decomposition of sugars, leading to the formation of caramel-like flavors and colors. This process occurs independently of amino acids and is purely a sugar affair.\n\nThe line between browning and burning is a fine one. Browning, as we've discussed, is the Maillard reaction and caramelization, resulting in delicious flavors and colors.",
